                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1123 Lincheng/133: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Schurman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1923-06-01T16:00:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 1, 1923—4 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received June 5—2:34 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>193. At a meeting at this Legation afternoon, May 31st, International Commission,
                    General Connor, President, received written instructions prepared as authorized
                    by diplomatic body by five ministers concerned and dean and then in conference
                    with Chinese general who is to accompany them they tentatively arranged the
                    program of their Lencheng visit. Besides two aides-de-camp General Connor takes
                    to assist him Colonel Barnes and Colonel Wainwright, New York state congressman,
                    who arrived here yesterday. Commission left Peking for Lincheng on 4.25 train
                    this afternoon.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Schurman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
